1 syllable <> 1 syllable words. For example: a, I, be
Closed syllables <> Syllables are divided according to the Closed syllables pattern. For example: into, also, very
Open syllables <> Syllables are divided according to the Open syllables pattern. For example: any, over, about
vc/cv <> Syllables are divided according to the vc/cv pattern. For example: into, also, only

2 syllables <> Words with 2 syllables. For example: any, into, also
3 syllables <> Words with 3 syllables. For example: family, another, area
4 syllables <> Words with 4 syllables. For example: economy, ability, American
5 or more syllables <> Words with 5 or more syllables. For example: opportunity, organisation, particularly
-s (Add as in gets) <> Suffix -s adds to the word with no changes. For example: say+s = says, get+s = gets, one+s = ones
-ed (Add) <> Suffix -ed adds to the word with no changes. For example: out+ed = outed, ask+ed = asked, own+ed = owned
-es (Add) <> Suffix -es adds to the word with no changes. For example: does + do+es,  go+es = goes
-less (Add) <> Suffix -less adds to the word with no changes. For example: un+less = unless, end+less = endless
-ness (Add) <> Suffix -ness adds to the word with no changes. For example: new+ness = newness, just+ness = justness, like+ness = likeness
-en (Add) <> Suffix -en adds to the word with no changes. For example: eat+en = eaten, beat+en = beaten, fall+en = fallen
-ing (Add) <> Suffix -ing adds to the word with no changes. For example: do+ing = doing, go+ing = going, say+ing = saying
-ful (Add) <> Suffix -ful adds to the word with no changes. For example: power+ful = powerful, wonder+ful = wonderful, success+ful = successful
-ish (Add) <> Suffix -ish adds to the word with no changes. For example: Jew+ish = Jewish, Brit+ish = British
-ist (Add) <> Suffix -ist adds to the word with no changes. For example: art+ist = artist, tour+ist = tourist, terror+ist = terrorist
-ing (Double as running) <> Suffix -ing doubles the last letter of the word. For example: running, getting, skipping
-ed (Double as tipped) <> Suffix -ed doubles the last letter of the word. For example: tipped, popped, fitted
-en (Double as forbidden) <> Suffix -en doubles the last letter of the word. For example: forbidden
-ish (Double as Scottish) <> Suffix -ish doubles the last letter of the word. For example: Scottish
-y (Add) <> Suffix -y adds to the word with no changes. For example: count+y = county, difficult+y = difficulty, guilt+y = guilty
-y (Double as snappy) <> Suffix -y doubles the last letter of the word. For example: snappy
-ly (Add) <> Suffix -ly adds to the word with no changes. For example: dry+ly = dryly, shy+ly = shyly, hot+ly = hotly
-ity (Change as activity) <> Suffix -ity changes the last letter of the word. For example: activity, security, community
-ility (Change as ability) <> Suffix -ility changes the last letter of the word. For example: ability, facility, possibility
-ty (Add) <> Suffix -ty adds to the word with no changes. For example: proper+ty = property, safe+ty = safety, special+ty = specialty
-ing (Drop) <> Suffix -ing drops the last letter of the stem. For example: use+ing = using, have+ing = having, make+ing = making
-ed (Drop) <> Suffix -ed drops the last letter of the stem. For example: time+ed = timed, like+ed = liked, state+ed = stated
-y (Drop) <> Suffix -y drops the last letter of the stem. For example: easy = easy, crazy
-en (Drop) <> Suffix -en drops the last letter of the stem. For example: taken, risen, shaken
-er (Add) <> Suffix -er adds to the word with no changes. For example: go+er = goer, say+er = sayer, new+er = newer
-er (Drop) <> Suffix -er drops the last letter of the stem. For example: timer, gamer, abler
-er (Double as bigger) <> Suffix -er doubles the last letter of the word. For example: bigger, cutter, redder
-ed=-d (Add) <> Suffix -ed-d adds to the word with no changes. For example: need, time+d = timed, out+ed = outed
